> On Oct 20, 2012, at 1:31 PM, Seth Hardy <shardy@asymptotic.ca> wrote:
>
> > hi. i work in this field (computer security) with a strong interest in
> > things like fair elections.
> >
> > years ago, i was talking to my mother - i mentioned that i was concerned
> > that there might be election fraud due to the diebold voting machines.
> she
> > said "that can't happen in america - we have bipartisan committees and
> > oversight and all sorts of things that prevent that kind of fraud. you're
> > just being paranoid. it would be all over the media if this happened."
> >
> > do a google search for diebold voting machines - when the report was
> > released (a couple years later), nobody dared go as far as to say that
> the
> > election was rigged, just that it would have been *really* easy using
> those
> > machines. that there is more security legally required on slot machines
> > than voting machines. i'm an expert in my field, and would not be
> surprised
> > if the 2000 or 2004 elections were rigged.
> >
> > there's a lot of conspiracy theory bullshit out there and a lot of
> reasons
> > to get pissed off, but when you immediately rail against someone for
> > spewing BS without doing any fact finding yourself, you're being just as
> > closed-minded. this was a serious issue with the diebold machines, and it
> > took years for the story to break in mainstream media outlets, so
> concerns
> > over bain buying up machines are, in my opinion, entirely legitimate.
> > enough to email the DOJ over something on a questionable website? maybe
> > not, but that doesn't mean the entire story is BS.
